                                    <p>A fundamental part of the Force.com platform is an “organisation” or “org”.</p>
 
                                    <p>At a high level, a Force.com org is a logical instance of data and metadata for a set of users. An org is bound by both capacity limits (number of users and storage) and execution computing resources (query sizes and API limits). These limits depend on your agreement with Salesforce.com and/or your license type.</p>
                                     
                                    <p>As part of the Force.com Enterprise Agreement we have the following limits:</p>
                                    
                                    <div class="margin-list">
                                        <li><strong>Platform Licenses:</strong> 49,076</li>
                                        <li><strong>Floating Platform Licenses:</strong> 120,000</li>
                                        <li><strong>Data Storage Limit:</strong> 5.6TB</li>
                                        <li><strong>File Storage Limit:</strong> 96.2TB</li>
                                        <li><strong>Max API Requests:</strong> 245,800,000 per day</li>
                                    </div>
                                     
                                    <p>Every user working on the Force.com platform will do so inside an org.</p>

                                    <h4>Lilly Force.com Org Overview:</h4>
                                    
                                    <div class="col_two_fifth">    
                                        <apex:image url="{!URLFOR($Resource.LAPD_ExtendedImages, 'extendedimages/forcetechnology/orgstrategy.jpg')}" alt="Org Strategy" />
                                    </div>

                                    <div class="col_three_fifth col_last">
                                        <p>The Global Services Org (GSO) Architecture is followed across all Cirrus owned environments.</p>

                                        <p>The Global Services Org (GSO1) is the primary enterprise environment for Lilly, covering all applications and services including quality critical and validated. Only approved vendors can develop for the GSO.</p>

                                        <p>The Citizen Developer Org (GSO2) is focused on “Speed to Value”, driving non-quality critical and non-validated applications and services developed by Lilly internal teams.</p>

                                        <p>The Patient Services Org (GSO3) is focused on “Patient Services” and is the highest security environment. Only approved vendors can develop for the GSO3.</p>

                                        <div class="margin-list">
                                            <li><strong>GSO1</strong> - Default Enterprise Environment</li>
                                            <li><strong>GSO2</strong> - Citizen Focused</li>
                                            <li><strong>GSO3</strong> - Patient Focused</li>
                                        </div>
                                    </div>     
                                </div>
                                <div class="tab-content clearfix" id="tabs-3">
                                    <div class="col_full bottommargin">
                                        <p>The Lilly Force.com Architecture (covering security, data governance, integrations, etc.) is known as the "Global Services Org (GSO) Architecture". As a result every org managed by Cirrus will have the codename "GSO", for example GSO1, GSO2, GSO3, etc.</p>
                                    </div>

                                    <div class="col_full bottommargin hidden-xs">
                                        <h4>GSO Logical Architecture Overview:</h4>
                                        <div class="divcenter center">
                                            <apex:image url="{!URLFOR($Resource.LAPD_ExtendedImages, 'extendedimages/forcetechnology/gsoarchitecture.jpg')}" alt="GSO Architecture" width="75%" />
                                        </div>
                                    </div>

                                    <h4>GSO Architecture Value Proposition:</h4>

                                    <p><strong>Capability Roadmap:</strong> The GSO is continuously improving through regular releases and the Force.com three release roadmap. All releases are seamless (managed by DevOps) and new features are available to all developers and existing applications instantly.</p>

                                    <p><strong>DevOps:</strong> Development in the GSO follows an agile methodology, with a application called Mission Control facilitating the end-to-end process. Development leverages high levels of automation via Continuous Integration techniques (DevOps Culture).</p>

                                    <p><strong>Integrations:</strong> The GSO is an API-Centric Architecture, meaning that every feature and capability can be accessed via RESTful web services. More complicated integration requirements are managed by a number of supported ETL integration services (e.g. Informatica).</p>

                                    <p><strong>Data:</strong> A number of master data sources have be pre-positioned in the GSO, providing native access to popular data (e.g. Employee, Customer, Product). These data sources are automatically synchronised and can be easily referenced or extended for custom development purposes.</p>

                                    <p><strong>Shared Services (AppExchange):</strong> To simplify development, the GSO includes a number of reusable services. These cover custom built applications (e.g. Customer Search Tool) and thousands of packages found on the Force.com AppExchange.</p>

                                    <p><strong>Security:</strong> Security is a core part of the GSO, which includes a suite if identity services (Onboarding, Authentication, Authorisation and Accounting), as well as a robust multi-tenant security model that is “Protect Lilly” approved for Red Data.</p>

                                    <p><strong>Force.com:</strong> The industry leading PaaS; instantly scalable, social enabled and mobile optimized.</p>
                                </div>
                                <div class="tab-content clearfix" id="tabs-4">
                                    <p>The Global Services Org (GSO) Architecture includes a suite of foundational capabilities to help simplify development, reduce costs through reuse and drive speed to value.</p>

                                    <h4>GSO Architecture Capabilities:</h4>

                                    <p><strong>User Management:</strong> All user access (profiles, permission sets, etc) will be managed via a centralised enterprise capability delivered by SailPoint IIQ, which helps guarantee that the GSO remains secure and controlled. For example, if a user changes roles or is off-boarded, their access permissions will automatically be updated in the GSO. As an application developer you don't need to do anything to enable this capability, it's available straight out of the box!</p>

                                    <p><strong>User Authentication:</strong> All user authentication will be managed via Lilly Single Sign-On (SSO). Therefore any application built in the GSO will automatically leverage SSO for web and mobile access, no additional setup or configuration is required!</p>

                                    <p><strong>Standard Integration Services and Data:</strong> One of the main challenges with any application development is gaining access to data (often hosted in Lilly). The GSO has a number of standard integration services, covering everything from batch to real-time. It also has pre-positioned data, that any application can instantly leverage (no new integrations required). For example, the GSO already has access to Employee data, Customer Master, Product Master, SAP, etc. The list of re-usable integrated services and data will continue to grow as more applications get developed, with Box, SharePoint, ServiceNow and Documentum already on the roadmap!</p>

                                    <p><strong>Standard Reusable Packages:</strong> The GSO has a suite of re-usable components, some will be custom applications written by Lilly (for example, the Customer Search Tool), while others will be installed from the AppExchange. The AppExchange has thousands of applications available that can be installed on the platform with a few simple clicks! A great example of an AppExchange application that is already installed is DocuSign, which enables eSignatures for Mercury. As DocuSign is connected to the platform (not specifically Mercury) it can be re-used by other Lilly Force.com applications.</p>

                                    <p><strong>Mobile Optimised (Salesforce1):</strong> Thanks to the Aura framework, all Force.com applications are end point agnostic, with no additional coding required. For example, if you open a Force.com application in the browser on a PC, you'll get served a user interface optimised for mouse and keyboard. However if you open the same application on a tablet or smartphone, the experience will instantly optimise for mobile. Essentially, develop once, use everywhere!</p>

                                    <p><strong>Social Enabled (Chatter):</strong> Alongside mobile optimisation, Force.com is social at its core, leveraging a capability known as Chatter to drive collaboration and provide context to data. The "working out loud" revolution has already changed the consumer world and it's widely expected that business is next!</p>

                                    <p><strong>Open APIs:</strong> Salesforce.com was a pioneer in API-Centric Architecture, meaning every Force.com feature and capability has a corresponding API, reducing "lock in" and enabling massive flexibility for developers. API-Centric design is the cornerstone of what is widely accepted as the next iteration of business development, where having a well-developed API is poised to be the way in which business relationships are established and maintained in a online, 24/7 digital economy (apievangelist.com). This is especially true in a world where everything is connected (people, devices, apps, data, etc).</p>
                                </div>
                                <div class="tab-content clearfix" id="tabs-5">
                                    <p>The Force.com PaaS is “not a silver bullet”. Its positioning is very specific and focused on a few key value propositions. To be successful it must be integrated into a broader IT eco-system. For example, Force.com is not designed to manage large quantities of unstructured data (e.g. video), therefore it must be integrated with another services such as Box and/or Kaltura.</p>
                                    <div class="divcenter center">
                                        <apex:image url="{!URLFOR($Resource.LAPD_ExtendedImages, 'extendedimages/forcetechnology/forcepositioning.jpg')}" alt="Force.com Positioning" width="95%" />
